for any corrections he might like to make. =20

 ECT purchased a quantity of "Elang Crude, suitable for export" from Phillip=
s=20
Petroleum Company ("Phillips"), and voyage-chartered the M/V PACIFIC VIRGO=20
from Mitsubishi Corporation ("Mitsubishi"),the time-charterer, to carry it=20
from Phillips' offshore loading facility in Indonesia to Thailand and the=20
Phillipines for use by the buyer, First Gas Power Corporation ("FGPC"), as=20
compressor fuel.  There exists a long-term compressor fuel agreement between=
=20
ECT and FGPC that contains several specifications that the product needed to=
=20
pass.  The agreement between ECT and Phillips does not mention any of these=20
specifications.   =20

 One of the specifications at issue from the ECT/FGPC agreement is  ASTM D=20
3605, which is used to test for the presence of certain metals.  According t=
o=20
ECT's surveyors, ASTM D 3605 apparently does not produce test results that=20
are sufficiently reproducible to be useful.  ECT has apparently been trying=20
for some months to convince FGPC of this, but without success.  FGPC=20
reportedly advises that Seimens, from whom it purchased the compressors at=20
issue, might void its warranty to FGPC if fuel is used that does not meet=20
ASTM D 3605. =20
=20
 A separate specification from the ECT/FGPC agreement, for sediments, may=20
also become at issue.  Months before the product at issue was loaded, ECT ha=
d=20
Elang Crude from this same facility tested to determine whether it would mee=
t=20
the FGPC specifications, and found that the Elang Crude was on-spec for ASTM=
=20
D 3605, but off-spec for sedimentation (again, a test separate and apart fro=
m=20
ASTM D 3605) by almost double the allowed amount.  It is not clear why ECT=20
decided to purchase  product from Phillips despite this test.  It is unknown=
=20
at this time whether this test included any of the product later loaded.  =20
=20
 At some point prior to loading, ECT did put the ship on notice that the=20
cargo had to meet specifications for use as compressor fuel.  The ship=20
responded by recommending that the tanks be Butterworthed, at an extra cost=20
(per the C/P) to ECT of $30,000.  ECT declined, apparently opting for a less=
=20
expensive fresh water rinse. Reportedly, the ship then advised that it did=20
not have sufficient fresh water to perform a fresh water (as opposed to=20
seawater) rinse.  I am not sure what tank cleaning ultimately took place, or=
=20
who paid for it.  SGS, ECT's surveyors, did deliver a dry certificate to us=20
before loading.=20
